{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}} {{Use British English|date=August 2017}} {{Infobox government agency |agency_name = National Records of Scotland |type = [[Non-ministerial government department]] |logo = National Records of Scotland logo.png |logo_width = |picture = |picture_width = |picture_caption = |formed = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|04|1}} |preceding1 = [[National Archives of Scotland]] |preceding2 = [[General Register Office for Scotland]] |jurisdiction = [[Scotland]] |headquarters = HM General Register House, 2 Princes Street, Edinburgh EH1 3YY |employees = 430 |budget = |minister1_name = [[Fiona Hyslop]] |minister1_pfo = [[Cabinet Secretary for Culture, Europe and External Affairs]] |chief1_name = Tim Ellis |chief1_position = Keeper of the Records / Registrar General |website = {{URL|http://www.nrscotland.gov.uk/}} }}
'''National Records of Scotland''' is a [[non-ministerial department]] of the [[Scottish Government]]. It is responsible for [[Civil registry|civil registration]], the [[census]] in [[Scotland]], [[demography]] and [[statistics]], [[family history]] and the [[national archives]] and historical records.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nationalrecordsofscotland.gov.uk/about-us/what-we-do |title=What we do |publisher=National Records of Scotland |accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>
National Records of Scotland was formed from the merger of the [[General Register Office for Scotland]] and the [[National Archives of Scotland]] in 2011, and combines all the functions of the two former organisations.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.gov.scot/News/Releases/2011/03/10144001 |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=2 October 2015 | publisher=[[Scottish Government]] | title=National Records of Scotland}}</ref>
The offices of [[Registrar General for Scotland]] and [[Keeper of the Records of Scotland]] both continue are combined in the person of Tim Ellis, Chief Executive of National Records of Scotland. <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gro-scotland.gov.uk/about-us | accessdate = 2 October 2015 | publisher =gro-scotland.gov.uk | title = About Us}}</ref>
==Location== [[File:HM General Register House, Edinburgh (geograph 2869117).jpg|thumb|View of Register House from North Bridge, looking across Princes Street.]] National Records of Scotland is based in HM General Register House on [[Princes Street]] in the [[New Town, Edinburgh|New Town]] in [[Edinburgh]]. The building was designed by [[Robert Adam]] for the Register House Trustees, and was opened to the public in 1788.
==History== :''For earlier history, see [[General Register Office for Scotland]] and [[National Archives of Scotland]]''.
The National Records of Scotland was created on 1 April 2011 by the merger of the [[General Register Office for Scotland]] and [[National Archives of Scotland]] and is a [[non-ministerial government department]] of the [[Scottish Government]]. It is part of the [[National Collections of Scotland]].
